          <h1>Projects</h1>
          <h2>Ukraine: Khmelnitsky Landfill, Khmelnitsky, Ukraine</h2>
            
              <p><em>Background</em><br />
              The Khmelnitsky  Landfill is a sanitary landfill owned by the Khmelnitsky City State  Administration and operated by Municipal Enterprise (ME) Spetskomuntrans. In  January 2010, Khmelnitsky Landfill brought a project online that is using  landfill gas (LFG) to fuel four  infrared heaters that have been installed in the landfill's maintenance garage.</p>
              <p>As a result of a 2007 U.S. Environmental Protection Agency  (U.S. EPA) grant and a concurrent U.S. EPA-sponsored <a href="../activities/actActivityDetailsForLandfill.aspx?myObjId=a07G000000K1EEWIA3&mySiteObjId=a09A00000098juSIAQ">landfill  assessment</a>, the Renewable Energy Agency (REA) installed four infrared  heaters in an outdoor landfill garage for bulldozers in the City of  Khmelnitsky, about 300 kilometers from Kiev. This is the first LFG-to-energy  project in Ukraine  and an example of a successful transfer of appropriate technology.</p>
              <p><em>Infrared heating  technology and capacity building</em><br />
                Infrared heating using LFG is ideal for facilities near  landfills with space heating needs. Infrared heating creates a high-intensity  energy that is safely absorbed by surfaces that warm up, which, in turn,  release heat to raise the ambient temperature. The technology is relatively simple  and inexpensive, and it can function effectively with a small gas flow. These  factors make Ukrainian landfills excellent candidates for this technology.</p>
              <p>Ukrainian landfills face operational challenges making  larger scale LFG energy projects difficult. The U.S. EPA provided  training to Ukrainian participants for this project, and this has led to the  successful operation of the technology at the landfill.</p>
              <p><em>Ukrainian landfill  sector potential</em><br />
                Ukrainian cities and towns generate approximately more than 10  million tons of municipal solid waste each year. More than 90 percent of this  waste is sent to landfills. About 140 of the estimated 700 landfills across the  country are considered suitable for extraction and utilization of landfill gas,  with the 90 largest landfills containing roughly 30 percent of the total amount  of municipal solid waste. Several pre-feasibility studies have been conducted  at Ukrainian landfills to assess the potential for project development.</p>
